releases.name: FelooPy v0.3.9
releases.body:
# What's New

- Multi-dimensional variables are now fully supported in heuristic optimization workflows.
- Encoded solutions in heuristic optimization can now be automatically decoded, streamlining post-processing.
- Binary, integer, and sequence variables are now accurately reported in model summaries and logs.
- The `load_from_excel` functionality in the Data Toolkit has been fixed and enhanced. A new `save_to_excel` feature has also been added for improved usability.
- Simulation of spatial datasets (e.g., points, distances) is now supported.
- Issues related to counting variables—particularly sequence variables—have been resolved, with improved reporting.
- The metric box now includes the following metrics, reported uniformly:
  - MGT – Model Generation Time  
  - CPT – Computational (CPU) Time  
  - DSR – Data Support Ratio  
  - DTD – Decision Tensor Density  
  - STG – Algorithm Stagnation  
  - OBJ – Objective Function Value  
  - OBJ ALT – Objective Function Value for an Alternative (i.e, a Pareto-Optimal Solution)
- A new model generation indicator has been added to track generation progress more effectively.
- `mdl.get` has been optimized for faster access to decision variables.
- `mdl.dvar` has been enhanced to better support dependent variables in heuristic optimization.
- Reports are now chiclet-style: modular and printable by section, useful for large industrial models.
- Heuristic optimization workflows (single- and multi-objective) are now easier to configure, with built-in encoder and decoder automation.
- Experimental support for NVIDIA cuOpt is now available for GPU-accelerated optimization.
- General stability improvements and bug fixes have been applied across the platform.

releases.name: FelooPy v0.3.8
releases.body:
What's new?

• Fully resolved dependencies—no more conflicts.
• Minor bug fixes & performance tweaks.
• Pass your dataset into the search operator to observe the magic.

releases.name: FelooPy v0.3.7
releases.body:
**What's new?**

- **Dependency Fixes:** Resolved issues with outdated or deprecated Python packages and NumPy types (`np.float`, `np.int`).  
- **Core Improvements:** Enhanced reporting, notifiers (search/model status), decision uncertainty handling, and model-data integration.  
- **Bug Fixes:** Corrected float values showing for binary/integer types and fixed logging issues (e.g., `pymprog`).  
- **New Features:**  
  - Added bounds checker for heuristics  
  - Warnings for `penalty_coefficient`  
  - Imprecision/unreliability checkers  
  - Data report box  
- **Solver & Interface Updates:**  
  - **Highspy 1.10.0:** Fixed deprecated NumPy type usage  
  - **Gekko 1.3.0:** Compatibility verified  
  - **CVXPY 1.6.4:** Highs solver supported; ECOS dropped  
  - **OR-Tools 9.12:** Supported; NumPy fixes applied  
  - **PyDecision 4.7.5:** Added LMAW & CPP-Tri algorithms  
  - **NiaPy 2.5.2:** Added (pending algorithm checks)  
  - **Xpress:** Supported; variable-adding method needs update

releases.name: FelooPy v0.3.6
releases.body:
## What is new?

- Project has moved from https://github.com/ktafakkori/feloopy to https://github.com/feloopy/feloopy
- Introducing `track_history=False/True` as a new search attribute, allowing visualization of trends using heuristic optimization algorithms.
- Introducing `flp.parallel_search()` to parallelize the solution environments over threads and processes.
- Introducing environment-based usage of multi-attribute decision-making methods.
- `m.sets()` or `flp.sets()` now accepts one or more than one set in defining for loops.
- `m.sum()` is now the best way to have summation expressions in the model.
- Fixed bugs in displaying decision variables.
- Fixed bugs in defining and using zero-dimensional variables in heuristic optimization.
- Updated the solvers (i.e., algorithms) provided by the `niapy` and `mealpy` heuristic optimization interfaces.
- Updated free solvers installable by `flp setup` or through the [FelooPy Engine](https://github.com/feloopy/engine).
- Introducing `save_io` as a new method for the data toolkit.
- Testing grad-heuristics (gradient-based optimizers of the machine learning field) for upcoming versions.
- Enhancing the consistency between FelooPy and the FelooPy engine.
- Numerous bug fixes and feature improvements.

info.author: Keivan Tafakkori
info.description:
Efficient & Feature-Rich Integrated Decision Environment

![PyPI](https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/feloopy?color=green&label=version&labelColor=grey) ![Release Date](https://img.shields.io/github/release-date/feloopy/feloopy?label=release&color=green&labelColor=grey) [![Downloads](https://static.pepy.tech/personalized-badge/feloopy?period=total&units=international_system&left_color=grey&right_color=green&left_text=downloads)](https://pepy.tech/project/feloopy) ![License](https://img.shields.io/static/v1?label=license&message=MIT&color=green&labelColor=grey)

### Quick Intro FelooPy (/fɛlupaɪ/) is a user-friendly tool for coding, modeling, and solving decision problems. It helps you focus on analysis and offers and supports a wide range of mathematical and statistical models and algorithms for decision-making.
### Quick Features - **Linear & Non-Linear Programming**: Exact algorithms for LP/NLP. - **Integer & Mixed-Integer Programming**: Exact algorithms for IP/MIP. - **General Purpose Programming**: Heuristic algorithms for various problems. - **Constraint Programming**: Techniques for constraint satisfaction. - **Multi-Objective Decision-Making**: Optimizing multiple objectives (MODM/MCDM). - **Multi-Attribute Decision-Making**: Evaluating opinions on alternatives using multiple attributes (MADM/MCDM).
### Quick Installation You can install `feloopy` inside a Python>=3.1x.x virtual environment: ```bash pip install -U "feloopy[stock]==0.3.9" ``` For supporting the developer, testing the latest version, and reporting bugs or contributing to the codebase, use: ```bash pip install "feloopy[stock] @ git+https://github.com/feloopy/feloopy.git" ```
### Quick Testing Here is an example to test FelooPy's functionality: ```python import feloopy as flp def example(m): x = m.bvar(name="x") y = m.pvar(name="y", bound=[0, 1]) m.con(x + y <= 1, name="c1") m.con(x - y >= 1, name="c2") m.obj(x + y) return m flp.search(example,directions=["max"]).clean_report() ```
